{"id":"340064769_Is_Bitcoin_a_decentralized_payment_mechanism","abstract":"We make a distinction between centralized, decentralized, and distributed payment mechanisms. A centralized payment mechanism processes a transaction using a trusted third party. A decentralized payment mechanism processes a transaction between the parties to the transaction. A distributed payment mechanism relies on the network of users to process a transaction on a shared ledger. We maintain that bitcoin is neither a centralized nor a decentralized payment mechanism. It is, instead, a distributed payment mechanism. We then consider decentralized and centralized aspects of the broader bitcoin payment space.","authors":["William J. Luther","Sean Stein Smith"],"meta":["March 2020Journal of Institutional Economics 16(4):1-12","DOI:10.1017/S1744137420000107"],"references":["338803648_Regulatory_ambiguity_in_the_market_for_bitcoin","327152770_Crypto_Public_Choice","326330078_Cryptodemocracy_and_its_institutional_possibilities","324660724_The_Institutional_Economics_of_Identity","270802537_Is_Bitcoin_a_Decentralized_Currency","351603194_The_Value_of_Bitcoin_in_the_Year_2141_and_Beyond","345363671_Is_bitcoin_money_And_what_that_means","338970965_Blockchain_and_the_evolution_of_institutional_technologies_Implications_for_innovation_policy","336264632_Capitalism_after_Satoshi_Blockchains_dehierarchicalisation_innovation_policy_and_the_regulatory_state","335985005_What_do_we_call_money_An_appraisal_of_the_money_or_non-money_view","334498467_Bitcoin's_Decentralized_Decision_Structure","333734016_Is_Bitcoin_Money_And_What_that_Means","331407350_Cash_Crime_and_Cryptocurrencies","326815368_Getting_off_the_ground_The_case_of_bitcoin","326567807_On_Distributed_Communications_Networks","322580171_Blockchains_and_the_economic_institutions_of_capitalism","318874909_Is_Bitcoin_Intrinsically_Worthless","318373290_Banning_Bitcoin","315309731_Regulating_Bitcoin_On_What_Grounds","313242640_Can_Bitcoin_Become_a_Majo